Common race condition: stale responses from out-of-order async operations.

```javascript
// Problem: user types fast, earlier request returns after later one
let currentRequestId = 0;

async function search(query) {
  const requestId = ++currentRequestId;
  const results = await fetch(`/api/search?q=${query}`).then(r => r.json());

  // Ignore stale responses
  if (requestId !== currentRequestId) return;
  displayResults(results);
}

// Better: use AbortController
let controller = null;

async function searchWithAbort(query) {
  controller?.abort();
  controller = new AbortController();

  try {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/search?q=${query}`, {
      signal: controller.signal
    });
    displayResults(await res.json());
  } catch (err) {
    if (err.name !== 'AbortError') throw err;
  }
}
```

AbortController is preferred because it actually cancels the request, saving bandwidth and server resources.

```javascript
function sleep(ms) {
  return new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, ms));
}

// Usage in async function
async function demo() {
  console.log('Start');
  await sleep(2000);
  console.log('2 seconds later');
}

// With AbortController for cancellation
function cancellableSleep(ms, signal) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    const timer = setTimeout(resolve, ms);
    signal?.addEventListener('abort', () => {
      clearTimeout(timer);
      reject(new Error('Cancelled'));
    });
  });
}
```

JavaScript has no built-in sleep. This Promise wrapper pauses async execution without blocking the event loop.

```javascript
const div = document.querySelector('#myDiv');

// textContent: gets/sets plain text only
div.textContent = '<b>Hello</b>';
// Renders as literal text: <b>Hello</b>

// innerHTML: gets/sets HTML markup
div.innerHTML = '<b>Hello</b>';
// Renders as: Hello (bold)

// innerText: like textContent but CSS-aware
// - Triggers reflow (slower)
// - Respects display:none
// - Returns visible text only
```

Security: `innerHTML` with user input creates XSS vulnerabilities. Always use `textContent` for user-provided strings. Use `innerHTML` only with trusted/sanitized content. `textContent` is faster than `innerText` because it doesn't trigger layout recalculation.

```javascript
// Euclidean algorithm (iterative)
function gcd(a, b) {
  a = Math.abs(a);
  b = Math.abs(b);
  while (b !== 0) {
    [a, b] = [b, a % b];
  }
  return a;
}

// Recursive
function gcdRecursive(a, b) {
  return b === 0 ? Math.abs(a) : gcdRecursive(b, a % b);
}

// LCM using GCD
function lcm(a, b) {
  return Math.abs(a * b) / gcd(a, b);
}

gcd(48, 18);   // 6
gcd(100, 75);  // 25
lcm(4, 6);     // 12
```

The Euclidean algorithm is O(log(min(a,b))). It works by repeatedly replacing the larger number with the remainder of dividing the two.

```javascript
const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
  entries.forEach(entry => {
    if (entry.isIntersecting) {
      entry.target.classList.add('visible');
      observer.unobserve(entry.target); // stop watching
    }
  });
}, {
  root: null,          // viewport
  rootMargin: '0px',
  threshold: 0.1       // 10% visible triggers callback
});

// Observe elements
document.querySelectorAll('.lazy-load').forEach(el => {
  observer.observe(el);
});
```

Use cases: lazy loading images, infinite scroll, scroll-based animations, analytics (tracking element visibility). Much more performant than scroll event listeners since it runs off the main thread.

```typescript
// Record utility type
type Scores = Record<string, number>;
const scores: Scores = { alice: 95, bob: 87 };

// Index signature
interface StringMap {
  [key: string]: string;
}

// Map type (runtime, any key type)
const cache = new Map<string, User>();

