`Record<K, V>` is preferred for type-safe dictionaries. Index signatures (`[key: string]`) are useful for open-ended objects. `Map` is best when you need non-string keys.

```javascript
Array.isArray([1, 2, 3]);    // true
Array.isArray('hello');       // false
Array.isArray({ length: 0 }); // false
Array.isArray(new Array());   // true
Array.isArray(Array.prototype); // true (it's an array!)

// Why not typeof?
typeof [1, 2, 3]; // 'object' — not helpful

// Why not instanceof?
[] instanceof Array; // true, but fails across frames/realms
// (each iframe has its own Array constructor)

// Array.isArray works across realms
const iframe = document.createElement('iframe');
document.body.appendChild(iframe);
const iframeArray = new iframe.contentWindow.Array();
iframeArray instanceof Array;     // false!
Array.isArray(iframeArray);       // true
```

`Array.isArray` is the only reliable method. It handles cross-realm arrays correctly.

`void` evaluates an expression and returns `undefined`:

```javascript
void 0;              // undefined
void 'hello';        // undefined
void (2 + 3);        // undefined

// Common uses:
// 1. Ensure undefined value
const UNDEF = void 0; // safer than using 'undefined' variable

// 2. Prevent navigation in href
<a href="javascript:void(0)">Click</a>

// 3. Arrow functions — discard return value
const log = (msg) => void console.log(msg);
// Returns undefined instead of console.log's return

// 4. IIFE without function keyword
void function() { console.log('runs'); }();
```

In modern code, `void 0` is rarely needed since `undefined` is not writable in strict mode. The arrow function use case is the most practical modern application.

```javascript
function selectionSort(arr) {
  const n = arr.length;
  for (let i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
    let minIdx = i;
    for (let j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
      if (arr[j] < arr[minIdx]) minIdx = j;
    }
    if (minIdx !== i) {
      [arr[i], arr[minIdx]] = [arr[minIdx], arr[i]];
    }
  }
  return arr;
}

selectionSort([64, 25, 12, 22, 11]);
// [11, 12, 22, 25, 64]
```

Selection sort finds the minimum in the unsorted portion and places it at the beginning. Time: O(n^2) in all cases. Space: O(1). Makes the minimum number of swaps (O(n)), which can matter when writes are expensive.

```javascript
// Map advantages over plain objects:
const map = new Map();

// 1. Any key type (objects, functions, primitives)
map.set({}, 'object key');
map.set(42, 'number key');

// 2. Guaranteed insertion order
// (objects also maintain order in modern engines, but Map is spec'd)

// 3. O(1) size
map.size; // fast
Object.keys(obj).length; // O(n)

// 4. Iterable directly
for (const [key, value] of map) { /* ... */ }

// 5. No prototype pollution
map.has('toString'); // false
obj.toString;        // exists (inherited)

// When to use objects:
// - JSON serialization needed
// - String keys only
// - Destructuring, spread
// - Static shape known at compile time
```

Use `Map` for dynamic collections. Use objects for structured records with known properties.

```typescript
// Object + as const
const Direction = {
  Up: 'UP',
  Down: 'DOWN',
  Left: 'LEFT',
  Right: 'RIGHT'
} as const;

type Direction = typeof Direction[keyof typeof Direction];
// 'UP' | 'DOWN' | 'LEFT' | 'RIGHT'

function move(dir: Direction) {
  switch (dir) {
    case Direction.Up: return 'Moving up';
    case Direction.Down: return 'Moving down';
    default: return 'Moving sideways';
  }
}

move(Direction.Up);  // OK
move('UP');          // OK
move('INVALID');     // Error
```

Benefits over `enum`: no runtime code generation, works with `as const` for literal types, tree-shakeable, and no reverse mapping overhead. This pattern is preferred by many TypeScript style guides.

```javascript
function isPrime(n) {
  if (n < 2) return false;
  if (n < 4) return true;
  if (n % 2 === 0 || n % 3 === 0) return false;

  for (let i = 5; i * i <= n; i += 6) {
    if (n % i === 0 || n % (i + 2) === 0) return false;
  }
  return true;
}

isPrime(2);    // true
isPrime(17);   // true
isPrime(100);  // false
isPrime(997);  // true
```

Optimizations: check 2 and 3 first, then only check numbers of form 6k +/- 1 (all primes > 3 are of this form). Only check up to sqrt(n). Time: O(sqrt(n)).

Tagged unions (discriminated unions) use a common literal property to distinguish variants:

```typescript
type Result<T> =
  | { status: 'success'; data: T }
  | { status: 'error'; message: string }
  | { status: 'loading' };

// Exhaustive switch
function handle<T>(result: Result<T>): string {
  switch (result.status) {
    case 'success': return `Got: ${result.data}`;
    case 'error': return `Error: ${result.message}`;
    case 'loading': return 'Loading...';
    default:
      const _exhaustive: never = result;
      return _exhaustive; // compile error if case missed
  }
}
```

Assigning to `never` in the default ensures a compile error if a new variant is added without handling it. This is the safest pattern for state management and API responses.

Every object has a hidden `[[Prototype]]` link. Property lookups walk this chain:

```javascript
const animal = {
  eats: true,
  walk() { return 'walking'; }
};

const dog = Object.create(animal);
dog.barks = true;

dog.barks;   // true (own property)
dog.eats;    // true (found on animal via prototype)
dog.walk();  // 'walking' (found on animal)
dog.toString(); // '[object Object]' (found on Object.prototype)

// Chain: dog -> animal -> Object.prototype -> null

Object.getPrototypeOf(dog) === animal;       // true
dog.hasOwnProperty('barks');                 // true
dog.hasOwnProperty('eats');                  // false
```

The chain ends at `Object.prototype`, whose prototype is `null`. This is how inheritance works in JavaScript — classes are syntactic sugar over this mechanism.

